Bathampton Down, Bath and North East Somerset, England
recordings.rmk:
Althought I did not see the bird, I believe this is a "chickadee" call from a Great Tit. Note the constant number of "chick" or "pee" notes at the beginning of the phrase, in this case three. The number of following "dee" sounds varies from two to four. 
This may be the fourth variety of churring described in "The vocabulary of the Great Tit" by Terry Gompertz (British Birds Vol.54 No.10, October 1961). He writes that this "is used between paired adults, notably when one is thwarted of the company of the other. Two or three short, separated churring notes are prefixed by two pee notes."
I note that my recording differs in the numbers of each note. 

Lightly edited below 2000 Hz due to some road noise.
